<h2>Group B: Attempts any EIGHT questions</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Prove that for every positive integer n ≥ 1, n<sup>2</sup>+n is even integer using mathematical induction.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Let p(n) = n<sup>2</sup> + n</p>
<p>First we perform basic steps</p>
<p>We show p(1) is true</p>
<p>i.e. p(1) = 1<sup>2</sup> + 1 = 2 (which is divisible by 2)</p>
<p>Hence, n<sup>2</sup> + n is an even integer when n = 1</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Induction Step:</strong></span></p>
<p>Let us suppose, for any arbitary k, p(k) is true. i,e, it is divisible by 2 so that it is an even integer.</p>
<p>i.e. k<sup>2</sup> + k = 2t, where t is an integer</p>
<p>Now, we have to show p(k + 1) is also even i.e. divisible by 2</p>
<p>(k + 1)<sup>2</sup>  + (k + 1)</p>
<p>= k<sup>2</sup> + 2k + 1 + k  + 1</p>
<p>= k<sup>2</sup> + k + 2k + 2</p>
<p>= 2t + 2k + 2</p>
<p>= 2t + 2(k+1)</p>
<p>= 2t + 2m (where m is an integer)</p>
<p>= 2(t+m)</p>
<p>= 2s (where is an integer)</p>
<p>Here, 2s is divisible by 2. Som p(x + 1) is an even integer. So, its true.</p>
<p>Hence, by matematical induction, n<sup>2</sup> + n is even whenever p ≥ 1</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>All over smart people are stupid. Children of stupid people are naughty. John is a children of Jane. Jane is over smart. Represent these statements in FOPL and prove that John is naughty.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Let x = total number of people</p>
<p>y = total children of people</p>
<p>OS(x) = x people are oversmart</p>
<p>S(x) = x people are stupid</p>
<p>C(y, x) = y childresn of x people</p>
<p>n(y) = y children are naughty</p>
<p>OS(jane) = Jane is oversmart</p>
<p>n(John) = John is naughty</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Promises:</strong></span></p>
<p>1)   ∀ x ( OS → S(x) )</p>
<p>2)  ∀ x, y ( S(x) ∧ C(y, x) → n(y) )</p>
<p>3)  OS (Jane)</p>
<p>4)    C(John, Jane)</p>
<p>Conclusion: n(John)</p>
